# Angular Component Patterns (Signals-Based)

This project uses Angular 20+. Always use the modern signal-based APIs. Never use legacy decorator-based patterns.

## Dependency Injection

Use the `inject()` function instead of constructor injection.

```typescript
// BAD - constructor injection
constructor(private themeService: ThemeService, private router: Router) {}

// GOOD - inject() function
readonly themeService = inject(ThemeService);
readonly router = inject(Router);
```

## Component Inputs

Use `input()` / `input.required()` signal functions instead of the `@Input()` decorator.

```typescript
// BAD - @Input decorator
@Input() label: string = '';
@Input({ required: true }) options: SelectOption[] = [];

// GOOD - input signal functions
label = input<string>('');
options = input.required<SelectOption[]>();
```

## Component Outputs

Use the `output()` function instead of the `@Output()` decorator with `EventEmitter`.

```typescript
// BAD - @Output decorator with EventEmitter
@Output() close = new EventEmitter<void>();
@Output() selectionChange = new EventEmitter<string>();

// GOOD - output function
close = output<void>();
selectionChange = output<string>();
```

## Two-Way Binding

Use `model()` instead of an `@Input()` + `@Output()` pair.

```typescript
// BAD - manual two-way binding
@Input() value: string = '';
@Output() valueChange = new EventEmitter<string>();

// GOOD - model signal
value = model<string>('');
```

## Reactive State & Derived Values

Use `signal()` for local mutable state, `computed()` for derived values, and `effect()` for side effects. Never use `get` accessors for derived reactive state.

```typescript
// BAD - getter that reads signals (not tracked properly, re-evaluates every CD cycle)
get displayText(): string {
  return this.selectedOption()?.label || this.placeholder();
}

// GOOD - computed signal
readonly displayText = computed(() => {
  return this.selectedOption()?.label || this.placeholder();
});

// GOOD - local mutable state
isOpen = signal<boolean>(false);

// GOOD - side effect reacting to signal changes
constructor() {
  effect(() => {
    if (this.disabled() && this.isOpen()) {
      this.closeDropdown();
    }
  });
}
```

## Standalone Components

All components should be standalone (the default in Angular 20). Do not set `standalone: true` explicitly as it is now the default -- just omit it. Import dependencies directly in the component's `imports` array.

## Lifecycle Hooks

Prefer `afterNextRender` / `afterRender` over `ngAfterViewInit` when performing DOM-related setup.

```typescript
// BAD
ngAfterViewInit() {
  this.setupChart();
}

// GOOD
constructor() {
  afterNextRender(() => {
    this.setupChart();
  });
}
```

## ViewChild / ContentChild

Use the signal-based query APIs.

```typescript
// BAD - decorator-based
@ViewChild('chart') chartRef!: ElementRef;

// GOOD - signal query
chartRef = viewChild<ElementRef>('chart');
chartRefRequired = viewChild.required<ElementRef>('chart');
children = viewChildren(ChildComponent);
contentChild = contentChild<ElementRef>('slot');
```
